Toggle navigation En français Browse Job Listings FAQ Contact Register Log in Log in Forgot password? 2024-09 - Indigenous Cultural Programmer North Vancouver , BC Description North Vancouver City Library is seeking two Indigenous cultural programmers to join our team on a temporary basis (20 hours per week for up to two years) to plan, develop, coordinate, and facilitate a variety of in-person and online public programming and events led by Indigenous people. Understanding the nature of specialized work such as this, we are open to considering one full-time programmer (35 hours per week for two years).As part of the Public Services team, the successful candidate(s) will have the opportunity to shape and lead public programs that center Indigenous voices, protocols and knowledge for audiences of all ages and backgrounds.The successful candidate will be able to demonstrate: Considerable knowledge and understanding of Indigenous culture, local traditions and protocols, and a desire to facilitate the sharing of that knowledge with Indigenous and non-Indigenous library customers Experience in the development and presentation of programs for all ages Ability to collaborate with others to plan and coordinate programs and/or community events Comfort with identifying and working with external partners, as well as Elders and knowledge keepers, to facilitate participation in library programs Existing positive relationships with local Nations, Indigenous organizations and individuals, and the ability to build relationships of respect and reciprocity with Indigenous people and communitiesA commitment to community service rooted in equity and respect is essential. This role will work with a variety of ages, including adults, children and youth, and families.One of City Library’s strategic priorities is to honour Indigenous perspectives. With the introduction of (an) Indigenous cultural programmer(s), we want Indigenous community members to see themselves respectfully reflected in library spaces and services, and to position the library as a partner authentically committed to reconciliation and decolonizing practices.Please see the Job Classification Specification below for further details.Qualifications: Completion of a post-secondary program or degree in library or information studies, education, art, history, anthropology or other relevant discipline, plus considerable experience working with and building relationships with Indigenous people, communities or organizations; or an equivalent combination of teachings, training and lived experience.Apply to: Deb Hutchison Koep, Chief Librarian, https://www.nvcl.ca/careers-libraryNote: When uploading documents to your profile, the maximum size allowed per document is 1MB. Please ensure the document file name and file extension is all lower case (i.e. .pdf and not .PDF). If you are having difficulty attaching documents, please click on the “question mark” icon on the top right side of the screen for technical support.Start date: ImmediatelySalary: $33.25 - $39.14/hour (pay grade 18; 2024 rates) + benefitsSchedule: The schedule for this position is flexible, but evening and weekend work will be required, including one mid-week evening and Saturday or Sunday. Schedules are reviewed periodically and subject to change.Closing date: September 2, 2024 at 5 p.m. or until filledNorth Vancouver City Library is committed to recruiting and hiring candidates that reflect the community we serve. We welcome applicants from diverse backgrounds, including Indigenous candidates, all identities, candidates who speak languages in addition to English, and persons with disabilities.Accommodations are available on request for candidates in all parts of the selection process.About us: North Vancouver City Library is located in the heart of the City of North Vancouver. As a valued public service, our library is a centre for discovery and dialogue, providing a gateway to lifelong learning and community connection through a balance of digital, traditional and emerging library services. Our decision-making is guided by deeply held values: https://www.nvcl.ca/about/missionClass Specification Class No. 582 - North Vancouver City LibraryINDIGENOUS CULTURAL PROGRAMMER1. Nature and Scope of WorkThis is specialized programming work which involves planning, developing, and delivering library programs that center Indigenous voices, protocols and knowledge for audiences of all ages. An incumbent identifies and assesses community needs, interests and opportunities; establishes and maintains strong relationships in the community and with partners; develops, coordinates and implements programs and activities for a variety of audiences; participates in library outreach in the community; and performs a variety of related administrative tasks. In addition, an incumbent participates in the implementation of initiatives related to supporting Indigenous community members, and contributes to the Indigenization and decolonization work of the library in general. An incumbent exercises considerable independence of judgement and action within the limits of established policies, procedures and guidelines. Unusual or difficult problems and policy matters are referred to a superior. Work performance is reviewed in terms of the quality and effectiveness of programs delivered, and conformance with defined standards.2. Illustrative Examples of WorkIdentifies and assesses community needs, interests and opportunities in order to inform, plan, develop and deliver library programs for both Indigenous and non-Indigenous audiences of all ages; as part of the programming team, researches and generates ideas for programming for a variety of audiences and delivery models.Plans, develops and implements library programs and activities that center Indigenous content, protocols and knowledge for Indigenous and non-Indigenous audiences of various ages; meets with community members, external partners and educators to discuss needs, interests and opportunities.Develops and coordinates program plans with consideration of defined outcomes, schedules, resources, audience and promotional needs; researches and prepares content and materials for programs; evaluates and recommends changes to programs and activities.Delivers programs and activities in the library and as part of library outreach activities; identifies and collaborates with external partners and persons such as elders or knowledge keepers to facilitate participation in library programs.Coordinates materials, services and equipment as required; arranges logistics for approved programs, activities and events; handles set-up and take down arrangements; participates in the development of promotional information and materials.Builds relationships with Indigenous community members; develops collaborative partnerships with other Indigenous programs, services and initiatives both internally and externally; works with individuals and groups to promote and encourage participation in programs, activities and events; acts as a liaison to connect individuals and organizations with library staff and services; represents the organization in community.Contributes to library plans, initiatives and activities around Indigenization and decolonization; contributes to implementation of initiatives related to supporting Indigenous library users and community members; serves as a resource and support for Indigenous knowledge; provides or supports training and provides resources to staff related to the delivery of programs and activities.Monitors budget and expenditures for program activities; prepares and maintains records, reports, materials and correspondence related to the work; performs a variety of administrative tasks in support of programs; maintains statistical records; maintains supplies and program materials.Performs related work as required.3. Required Knowledge, Abilities and SkillsConsiderable knowledge and understanding of the social and political structures, cultures, histories and ways of knowing, being and doing in local First Nations or urban Indigenous communities, with knowledge of Indigenous languages an asset.Considerable knowledge of the history of Indigenous peoples in Canada, the impacts of colonization, and the barriers Indigenous peoples face.Sound knowledge of the principles, practices, methods and objectives of public, educational and cultural programming, from planning and development through to evaluation, for a variety of audiences.Sound knowledge of the interests, needs and resources of the communities served.Working knowledge of Indigenous organizations located in the region and partnership opportunities.Working knowledge of the library’s programs, services, resources, operations and related requirements.Ability to plan, coordinate, develop, deliver, promote and evaluate a variety of programs and events for a variety of audiences that demonstrate and promote culture humility and cultural safety.Ability to build relationships of respect and reciprocity with Indigenous people and communities.Ability to establish and maintain effective and respectful working relationships with a variety of internal and external contacts, and to promote interest, collaboration and participation in programs.Ability to deal effectively and courteously with the public, provide information, interpret and explain library policies and regulations, and to demonstrate judgment and sensitivity in challenging conversations.Ability to communicate effectively orally and in writing, and make presentations related to the work.Ability to prepare and maintain a variety of records, reports and files related to the work.Ability to operate standard office equipment and use software related to the work.4. Desirable Training and ExperienceCompletion of a post-secondary program or degree in library or information studies, education, art, history, anthropology or other relevant discipline, plus considerable experience working with and building relationships with Indigenous people, communities or organizations; or an equivalent combination of teachings, training and lived experience.5. Required Licenses, Certificates and Registrations - None. Compensation $33.25 - $39.14/hour (pay grade 18; 2024 rates) + benefits Closes: 30 September, 2024 North Vancouver City Library North Vancouver , BC Policies and Terms of Use · jobboard@bcla.bc.ca / BCLA PO BOX 19008, Rocky Point PO, Port Moody, BC V3H 0J1 window.dataLayer = window.dataLayer || [];
